"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520858","Home Office","false","2016-06-06","<p>The family reunion policy allows those granted refugee status or humanitarian protection in the UK to sponsor their pre-flight family members, i.e. spouse or partner and children under the age of 18, who formed part of the family unit before the sponsor fled their country, to reunite with them in the UK.</p><p>Information on the applicant’s relationship with their sponsor is not collated centrally. As such it is not possible to identify how many applicants have applied for family reunion as adult children aged 18 or over or what the outcome was.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","38031","2016-06-06T16:17:08.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520858/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520858/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520858/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-23","Asylum: Families","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many unsuccessful refugee family reunion applications during the last three years were rejected on the basis of the child being 18 years or older.","false","Biography information for Stuart C. McDonald","Cumbernauld, Kilsyth and Kirkintilloch East","Stuart C. McDonald","38032"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520859","Home Office","false","2016-06-06","<p>The available published statistics relate to the 'Family: other' category, which are known to very largely consist of family reunion cases. The information is provided in the table below.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="5"><p><strong>Entry clearance visas (cases resolved </strong><em>of which</em><strong>: grants, refusals, withdrawn/lapsed): Family Other<strong>[2]</strong></strong></p></td></tr><tr><td rowspan="2"><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td rowspan="2"><p><strong>Cases resolved</strong></p></td><td colspan="3"><p><em>of which:</em></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Granted</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Refused</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Withdrawn or lapsed</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>6,108</p></td><td><p>4,211</p></td><td><p>1,797</p></td><td><p>100</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>6,658</p></td><td><p>4,596</p></td><td><p>1,931</p></td><td><p>131</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>8,544</p></td><td><p>4,949</p></td><td><p>3,466</p></td><td><p>129</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="5" rowspan="2"><p><strong>Source:</strong><br>Immigration Statistics Oct - Dec 2015, Visas volume 1 table vi_01_q.</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>[1] For the year 2015 family reunion visas made up 99% of “Family: Other” visas granted.</p><p>[2] The “Family: Other” category consists of:</p><ul><li>Family reunion: pre-existing family members (partners, minor children) of a person with refugee leave or humanitarian protection, who has not yet obtained British citizenship;</li><li><em>From July 2012</em>: dependants who are not partners or children of those with refugee leave or humanitarian protection;</li><li><em>From July 2012</em>: parents with access rights to a child.</li></ul><p> </p><p>The latest quarterly Home Office immigration statistics on entry clearance visas are published in 'Immigration Statistics', available from the Home Office website at: https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/migration-statistics</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-06-06T16:18:47.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520859/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520859/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520859/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-23","Asylum: Families","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many (a) successful and (b) unsuccessful refugee family reunion applications there have been in the last three years.","false","Biography information for Stuart C. McDonald","Cumbernauld, Kilsyth and Kirkintilloch East","Stuart C. McDonald","38033"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520860","Home Office","false","2016-05-26","<p>The Home Office do not hold the information requested.</p><p>However, we have introduced an ‘online flag’ as part of the police recorded crime data collection. This allows police forces to record online instances of abuse and other crimes such as stalking, harassment, sexual offences and others. These offences could have taken place solely online, or had an online element to them. These data are currently still in development but will be published in due course. However, it will not be possible to split the data according to type of social media used (if any).</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-05-26T15:43:07.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520860/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520860/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520860/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-23","Social Media","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many cases of online abuse on (a) Facebook, (b) Twitter and (c) all other social media have been reported to the police since 2010.","false","Biography information for Andrew Percy","Brigg and Goole","Andrew Percy","37988"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520861","Home Office","false","2016-06-01","<p>The Home Office do not hold the information requested. The Ministry of Justice hold data on the number of offenders found guilty at all courts in England and Wales.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2016-06-01T13:50:38.283Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520861/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520861/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520861/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-23","Social Media","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many people have been convicted of offences of online abuse on (a) Facebook and (b) Twitter under the Communications Act 2003 since 2010.","false","Biography information for Andrew Percy","Brigg and Goole","Andrew Percy","37989"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520862","Home Office","false","2016-05-26","<p>The UK Council for Child Internet Safety (UKCCIS) is co-chaired by Ministers from Department for Education, Home Office and Department for Culture Media and Sport. This brings together industry, law enforcement, academia, charities and parenting groups to help to keep children and young people safe online. As part of this work, the UK’s Communications regulator, Ofcom, published best practice guidance for social media platforms to encourage responsible practice from industry in December 2015.</p><p>The Department for Education recognises that educating young people is key to tackling cyberbullying and protecting children from online abuse. All schools must have a behaviour policy which includes measures to prevent and tackle all forms of bullying, including cyberbullying. To help schools to develop effective measures the Department for Education has produced advice which provides a definition of cyberbullying and outlines the steps schools can take to deal with bullying.</p><p>Search powers included in the Education Act 2011 have given teachers stronger powers to tackle cyber-bullying (via text message or the internet) by providing a specific power to search for and, if necessary, delete inappropriate images (or files) on electronic devices, including mobile phones. The Department has also issued advice for parents and carers on cyberbullying which specifies the tell-tale signs that it is happening and includes advice on what do when it occurs.</p><p>The Government has invested £3.85 million in a new phase of our This is Abuse campaign, which tackles abuse within teenage relationships and was launched in March. The National Crime Agency’s Child Exploitation and Online Protection (CEOP) has developed a comprehensive education programme, called Thinkuknow, which provides targeted advice to children, parents and carers, including on how to use social media safely.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2016-05-26T16:05:33.903Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520862/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520862/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520862/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-23","Internet: Bullying","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what discussions she has had with the Secretary of State for Education on tackling online abuse in schools.","false","Biography information for Andrew Percy","Brigg and Goole","Andrew Percy","37990"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520863","Home Office","false","2016-06-06","<p>The family reunion policy allows those granted refugee status or humanitarian protection in the UK to sponsor their pre-flight family members, i.e. spouse or partner and children under the age of 18, who formed part of the family unit before the sponsor fled their country, to reunite with them in the UK.</p><p>Information on the applicant’s relationship with their sponsor is not collated centrally. As such it is not possible to identify how many applicants have applied for family reunion as adult children aged 18 or over or what the outcome was.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","38032","2016-06-06T16:17:08.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520863/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520863/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520863/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-23","Asylum: Families","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many refugee family reunion applications to bring children of 18 years or older into the UK were submitted in the last three years; and how many of those applications were successful.","false","Biography information for Stuart C. McDonald","Cumbernauld, Kilsyth and Kirkintilloch East","Stuart C. McDonald","38031"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520864","Home Office","false","2016-06-06","<p>There are no service standards for a change of conditions application.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-06-06T16:01:50.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520864/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520864/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520864/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-23","Immigration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether her Department has service standards for considering applications for the change of conditions of leave granted on the basis of family or private life.","false","Biography information for Mr Andrew Smith","Oxford East","Mr Andrew Smith","38021"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520865","Home Office","false","2016-05-25","<p>The Home Office collects data on the number of full-time equivalent (FTE) officers on certified long-term sick leave as at 31 March each year. This can be broken down by those on long-term sick leave as a result of assault, and those on long-term sick leave for other reasons. Long-term sick includes officers on leave for 28 days or more.</p><p>The latest published data shows that there were 16 officers (FTE) on long-term sick leave in the Cumbria Constabulary, as at 31 March 2015. None of these were following assaults.</p><p>Data on the number of officers on short/medium-term absence due to sickness are published by Her Majesty’s Inspectorate of Constabulary, and show that 16 officers were on short/medium-term sick leave as at 31 March 2015. These data do not identify the reasons for the absence.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-05-25T14:28:30.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520865/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520865/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520865/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-23","Cumbria Constabulary: Sick Leave","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many police officers in Cumbria Constabulary are absent from work as a result of sickness or injuries caused by violence inflicted on them in the course of their duties.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","38005"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520866","Home Office","false","2016-05-25","<p>The Home Office does not collect this information. The manner in which police officers are deployed is an operational decision for chief officers, in line with local priorities and held to account by police and crime commissioners.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-05-25T14:28:19.07Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520866/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520866/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520866/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-23","Cumbria Constabulary","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many incidents in the Cumbria Constabulary area were responded to by a single officer in each year since 2012.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","38006"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520867","Home Office","false","2016-06-06","<p>The UK Government takes it’s responsibility in all cases involving children seriously and we will continue to ensure that all unaccompanied children are provided with appropriate care, regardless of their route to the UK.</p><p>It is important that we work with local authorities to understand their capacity to support all unaccompanied children and ensure their needs can be met. That is why my officials are working closely with the Department for Communities and Local Government and the Department for Education to ensure consultation with local authorities is consistent and coordinated across all resettlement and relocation programmes. Consultation with local government partners will take place over the coming weeks and Parliament will be updated in due course.</p><p>We are keen to ensure that there is a more equitable distribution of unaccompanied children across the UK and that no local authority is required to take more children than they can support.</p><p>The Home Office provides funding to local authorities for the care of unaccompanied asylum seeking children and recently announced new enhanced rates to support the transfer scheme. We will continue to measure the impacts on local authorities, but are clear that funding for unaccompanied asylum seeking children and refugees must be aligned, regardless of the route of entry for the child.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","37889 ; 38028","2016-06-06T17:04:36.27Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520867/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520867/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520867/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-23","Refugees: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what criteria the Government plans to use to assess the suitability of a local authority's capacity to provide suitable care for resettled children under the Immigration Act 2016.","false","Biography information for Mr Nicholas Brown","Newcastle upon Tyne East","Mr Nicholas Brown","38014"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520868","Home Office","false","2016-05-26","<p>This information is not centrally held. Border Force works with a range of partners, including law enforcement agencies from the UK and overseas to share intelligence used to identify potentially dangerous and undesirable individuals who are seeking to travel to and enter the UK.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-05-26T13:00:31.14Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520868/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520868/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520868/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-23","Immigration Controls: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many people from the A2 countries of the EU were stopped at border control as a result of intelligence shared by the authorities of those countries in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Liam Byrne","Birmingham, Hodge Hill","Liam Byrne","37923"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520869","Home Office","false","2016-05-26","<p>The UK exchanges criminal records information with the A2 countries - Bulgaria and Romania - as a result of the UK’s participation in the European Criminal Records Information System (ECRIS).</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-05-26T13:00:00.703Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520869/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520869/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520869/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-23","Criminal Records: EU Countries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what criminal record-sharing facilities exist between the UK and the A2 countries of the EU; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Liam Byrne","Birmingham, Hodge Hill","Liam Byrne","37954"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520870","Home Office","false","2016-05-25","<p>The decision on the deployment of available resources, including roles for chief superintendents, are operational matters for individual chief constables, working with their police and crime commissioners.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-05-25T14:28:46.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520870/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520870/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520870/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-23","Nottinghamshire Police","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, for what reasons the role of chief superintendent for Nottingham at Nottinghamshire Police  was removed on 1 May 2016; what consultation was carried out prior to that decision being made; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Graham Allen","Nottingham North","Mr Graham Allen","37960"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520871","Home Office","false","2016-05-25","<p>The Home Office does not hold information about the personal pension entitlement of any individual police officer.</p><p>Arrangements for the pensionable pay of chief officers on temporary promotion to a higher rank are set out in determinations made under the Police Regulations 2003. These state that after 28 days spent performing the duties of a chief constable, a deputy chief constable will be paid either a temporary salary (pensionable) at a rate equivalent to 90% of the higher rank’s basic pay or an honorarium (a non-pensionable payment) of an amount to be determined by the local policing body.</p><p>Pensionable pay is taken into account in calculating pension contributions and pension benefits, whereas any non-pensionable payments are not.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-05-25T14:29:16.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520871/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520871/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520871/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-23","Nottinghamshire Police","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the effect will be on the pension entitlement of the Deputy Chief Constable of Nottinghamshire Police of her promotion to acting Chief Constable.","false","Biography information for Mr Graham Allen","Nottingham North","Mr Graham Allen","37961"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520872","Home Office","false","2016-06-06","<p>There are no plans to extend the family reunion criteria. The current policy meets our international obligations and strikes the right balance.</p><p>Where family members cannot meet the requirements of the Immigration Rules, such as in the case of an 18 year old applying to join their refugee parents in the UK, we consider whether there are exceptional circumstances or compassionate reasons to justify granting entry clearance outside the Rules.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-06-06T16:22:51.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520872/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520872/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520872/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-23","Asylum: Families","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will consider proposals put forward by the British Red Cross Torn Apart campaign to extend refugee family reunion to include young people over the age of 18 who were living with their parents when they were forced to flee.","false","Biography information for Stuart C. McDonald","Cumbernauld, Kilsyth and Kirkintilloch East","Stuart C. McDonald","37784"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520873","Home Office","false","2016-06-06","<p>The table attached shows the number of people removed on leaving detention, by nationality who were held for over six and over twelve months.</p><p>Published statistics relating to immigration detention are only available from 2010 onwards. It is not possible to provide pre-2010 figures and this information could be provided only by examining individual case records, which would result in disproportionate cost.</p><p>The Home Office publishes quarterly and annual statistics on the number of people detained in the United Kingdom for immigration purposes, within the Immigration Statistics release on the GOV.UK website:</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/home-office/series/immigration-statistics-quarterly-release</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","37779","2016-06-06T16:34:25.193Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520873/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520873/answer","Table 37778 with 37779.xlsx","Table 37778 with 37779.xlsx","People removed on leaving detention","People removed on leaving detention","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520873/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-23","Immigrants: Detainees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many people of each nationality detained for over (a) six and (b) 12 months between 2005 and 2015 for the purpose of removal were successfully removed.","false","Biography information for Stuart C. McDonald","Cumbernauld, Kilsyth and Kirkintilloch East","Stuart C. McDonald","37778"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520874","Home Office","false","2016-06-06","<p>The table attached shows the number of people removed on leaving detention, by nationality who were held for over six and over twelve months.</p><p>Published statistics relating to immigration detention are only available from 2010 onwards. It is not possible to provide pre-2010 figures and this information could be provided only by examining individual case records, which would result in disproportionate cost.</p><p>The Home Office publishes quarterly and annual statistics on the number of people detained in the United Kingdom for immigration purposes, within the Immigration Statistics release on the GOV.UK website:</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/home-office/series/immigration-statistics-quarterly-release</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","37778","2016-06-06T16:34:25.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520874/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520874/answer","Table 37778 with 37779.xlsx","Table 37778 with 37779.xlsx","People removed on leaving detention","People removed on leaving detention","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520874/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-23","Immigrants: Detainees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many people of each nationality were held in detention for over (a) six and (b) 12 months between 2005 and 2015 for the purpose of removal.","false","Biography information for Stuart C. McDonald","Cumbernauld, Kilsyth and Kirkintilloch East","Stuart C. McDonald","37779"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520875","Home Office","false","2016-06-06","<p>The information requested is not routinely collected and could be provided only by examining individual case records, which would result in disproportionate cost.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-06-06T16:04:44.24Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520875/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520875/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520875/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-23","Immigrants: Detainees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many people of each nationality detained between 2005 and 2015 for the purpose of removal had been previously detained for the same purpose and released.","false","Biography information for Stuart C. McDonald","Cumbernauld, Kilsyth and Kirkintilloch East","Stuart C. McDonald","37780"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520876","Cabinet Office","true","2016-06-01","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2016-06-01T15:36:36.027Z","2016-06-02T13:22:50.933Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520876/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520876/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520876/answer","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520876/answer/previousversion/1505","Table 1 Passports Held Summary Statistics.docx ; Table 2 Passports Held by the Usually Resident Population in England and....docx ; UKSA response to PQ37800.pdf","Attachment 1 for Member ; Attachment 2 for Member ; UKSA Letter to Member - Non-EU Country Passports","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520876/answer/previousversion/1505","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-05-23","Passports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many people resident in the UK hold an EU non-British passport and previously held a non-EU country passport.","false","Biography information for Kevin Hollinrake","Thirsk and Malton","Kevin Hollinrake","37800"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520877","Home Office","false","2016-06-01","<p>The Home Office does not set a budget for food produced for its offices. Catering services are provided by private companies under contract at Home Office buildings and provided to staff without subsidy. Details of the proportion of food produced for the Home Office that was sourced from British producers could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2016-06-01T13:52:50.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520877/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520877/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520877/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-23","Home Office: Food","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the annual budget is for food produced for her Department's offices; and what proportion of food produced for her Department was sourced from British producers in the last period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Nick Smith","Blaenau Gwent","Nick Smith","37829"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520878","Home Office","false","2016-05-26","<p>The statistics provided by the National Crime Agency on their website: http://www.nationalcrimeagency.gov.uk/publications/european-arrest-warrant-statistics are not broken down in the manner requested (i.e., by gender). Additionally they are only available by offence-type from calendar year 2010.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-05-26T13:01:39.78Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520878/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520878/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520878/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-23","European Arrest Warrants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many European Arrest Warrant surrenders (a) to and (b) from each UK law enforcement agency there have been of people suspected of violent, sexual or other offences against women in each year since 2004; and of which offence each of those people was suspected.","false","Biography information for Jack Dromey","Birmingham, Erdington","Jack Dromey","37842"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520879","Home Office","false","2016-06-06","<p>The UK Government takes it’s responsibility in all cases involving children seriously and we will continue to ensure that all unaccompanied children are provided with appropriate care, regardless of their route to the UK.</p><p>It is important that we work with local authorities to understand their capacity to support all unaccompanied children and ensure their needs can be met. That is why my officials are working closely with the Department for Communities and Local Government and the Department for Education to ensure consultation with local authorities is consistent and coordinated across all resettlement and relocation programmes. Consultation with local government partners will take place over the coming weeks and Parliament will be updated in due course.</p><p>We are keen to ensure that there is a more equitable distribution of unaccompanied children across the UK and that no local authority is required to take more children than they can support.</p><p>The Home Office provides funding to local authorities for the care of unaccompanied asylum seeking children and recently announced new enhanced rates to support the transfer scheme. We will continue to measure the impacts on local authorities, but are clear that funding for unaccompanied asylum seeking children and refugees must be aligned, regardless of the route of entry for the child.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","38014 ; 38028","2016-06-06T17:04:36.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520879/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520879/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520879/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-23","Refugees: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what support the Government provides local authorities who express an interest in resettling refugee children under the Immigration Act 2016.","false","Biography information for Mr Nicholas Brown","Newcastle upon Tyne East","Mr Nicholas Brown","37889"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520880","Department for Education","false","2016-05-26","<p>The Government has no plans to amend adoption legislation to facilitate the adoption of children resettled under the Immigration Act 2016. The United Nations and other humanitarian charities advise that no new adoption applications should be considered in the period after a disaster or from a war zone before the authorities in that State are in a position to apply the necessary safeguards. This is because it is not uncommon in an emergency or unsettled situation for children to be temporarily separated from their parents or other family members who may be looking for them. So whilst some lone refugee children may come to the UK for temporary care, we would wish to support them to be reunited with their parents or other relatives where this is possible.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2016-05-26T16:44:06.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520880/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520880/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520880/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-05-23","Intercountry Adoption","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what plans the Government has to amend adoption rules to facilitate the adoption of children resettled under the Immigration Act 2016.","false","Biography information for Mr Nicholas Brown","Newcastle upon Tyne East","Mr Nicholas Brown","37888"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520881","Home Office","false","2016-06-06","<p>Information on how many EU nationals have won appeals to prevent their removal from the UK in each of the last 10 years is not held centrally.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-06-06T16:03:11.713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520881/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520881/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520881/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-23","Deportation: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many nationals of other EU member states have won appeals to prevent their removal from the UK in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Mr Dominic Grieve","Beaconsfield","Mr Dominic Grieve","37904"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520882","Home Office","false","2016-06-06","<p>We intend to publish revised country information and guidance on handling claims made by Eritrean nationals in the near future.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-06-06T16:25:39.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520882/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520882/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520882/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-23","Asylum: Eritrea","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to the Answer of 12 May 2016 to Question 36796, when she expects to publish the updated country information and guidance on handling asylum claims made by Eritrean nationals.","false","Biography information for Mike Kane","Wythenshawe and Sale East","Mike Kane","37911"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520883","Home Office","false","2016-05-26","<p>The European Arrest Warrant is designed to speed up the process of extradition. As set out in Command Paper Cm 8897 (Decision pursuant to Article 10(5) of Protocol 36 to The Treaty on the Functioning of the European Union), in terms of average time taken for surrender from the UK to another country, it takes on average about three months to extradite someone under a European Arrest Warrant. Extradition to relevant non-EU countries takes on average about ten months but can, and often does, take considerably longer. Time limits are shorter under the European Arrest Warrant than under the European Convention on Extradition, resulting in shorter times in custody overall.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","37843","2016-05-26T12:59:15.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520883/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520883/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520883/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-23","Extradition","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the average time taken to extradite suspected criminals is from category 2 (a) Type A and (b) Type B territories.","false","Biography information for Jack Dromey","Birmingham, Erdington","Jack Dromey","37847"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520884","Home Office","false","2016-05-26","<p>The European Arrest Warrant is designed to speed up the process of extradition. As set out in Command Paper Cm 8897 (Decision pursuant to Article 10(5) of Protocol 36 to The Treaty on the Functioning of the European Union), in terms of average time taken for surrender from the UK to another country, it takes on average about three months to extradite someone under a European Arrest Warrant. Extradition to relevant non-EU countries takes on average about ten months but can, and often does, take considerably longer. Time limits are shorter under the European Arrest Warrant than under the European Convention on Extradition, resulting in shorter times in custody overall.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","37847","2016-05-26T12:59:15.713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520884/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520884/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520884/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-23","Extradition","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the average time taken was to extradite suspected criminals from countries covered by the provisions of European Arrest Warrant scheme (a) before and (b) in each year after the Extradition Act 2003 came into force.","false","Biography information for Jack Dromey","Birmingham, Erdington","Jack Dromey","37843"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520885","Home Office","false","2016-05-26","<p>The Home Office does not hold data centrally on the number of arrests of people from A2 countries of the EU.</p><p>The Home Office collect and publish data on the number of arrests broken down by offence group, gender, age group and ethnicity. The Home Office does not collect data on the nationality of those arrested.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-05-26T11:34:11.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520885/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520885/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520885/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-23","Arrests: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many people from the A2 countries of the EU were arrested in each of the last five years for which records are available.","false","Biography information for Liam Byrne","Birmingham, Hodge Hill","Liam Byrne","37922"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520886","Home Office","false","2016-05-25","<p>A community resolution is a voluntary agreement between the victim and offender to a low level crime where the offender has admitted responsibility and as such is unenforceable.</p><p>If an officer has concerns at the outset that the offender may not comply an alternative course of action should be taken.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-05-25T14:28:02.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520886/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520886/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520886/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-23","Alternatives to Prosecution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps law enforcement agencies can take to ensure that community resolution agreements are honoured.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","37906"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520887","Home Office","false","2016-05-26","<p>The Home Office publishes the number of Community Resolutions issued and recorded by police forces as part of its Crime Outcomes in England and Wales statistical releases. These show Community Resolutions that have been delivered in accordance with the College of Policing guidance on the Use of Community Resolution Incorporating Restorative Justice.</p><p>The latest figures show that in year ending December 2015 there were 120,002 Community Resolutions recorded by police forces in England and Wales.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-05-26T15:20:42.183Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520887/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520887/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520887/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-23","Alternatives to Prosecution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how community resolution agreements are recorded in crime statistics.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","37907"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520888","Department for International Development","false","2016-05-31","<p>Department for International Development does not set a budget for food served in its Department’s offices. Catering services are provided by a private company under contract to Department for International Development and provides food to staff without subsidy. Spending on food is determined by the contractor based on sales receipts from DFID staff.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2016-05-31T14:47:30.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520888/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520888/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520888/answer",,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-05-23","Department for International Development: Food","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what the annual budget is for food produced for her Department's offices; and what proportion of food produced for her Department was sourced from British producers in the last period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Nick Smith","Blaenau Gwent","Nick Smith","37830"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520889","Department for International Development","false","2016-05-31","<p>The UK provides substantial funding to international NGOs and UN agencies, enabling them to respond to disasters around the world, including Sri Lanka. This includes the Central Emergency Response Fund (CERF) , which was established by the UN and other leading donors to enable rapid emergency response. The CERF is doing an assessment of the situation following the rainfall and landslips in Sri Lanka. The UK, along with other leading donors, will provide support as required through this coordinated response mechanism.</p><p>The UK is the biggest contributor to the CERF, having provided in excess of $855m in the last 10 years. The UK also provides funding to the European Union humanitarian agency (ECHO) which is also undertaking an assessment.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2016-05-31T14:49:59.83Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520889/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520889/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520889/answer",,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-05-23","Sri Lanka: Floods","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assistance her Department is providing to people affected by flooding in Sri Lanka.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","38035"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520890","Department for International Development","false","2016-05-31","<p>At the World Humanitarian Summit this week the UK reaffirmed its commitment to promoting and enhancing the protection of civilians and civilian objects, by strengthening compliance with International Law. We condemn targeting of civilians and the indiscriminate or disproportionate use of any weapon.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2016-05-31T14:48:31.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520890/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520890/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520890/answer",,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-05-23","Developing Countries: Explosives","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, if she will make a commitment at the World Humanitarian Summit 2016 to work to prevent harm from the use of wide-area explosive weapons in populated areas.","false","Biography information for Thangam Debbonaire","Bristol West","Thangam Debbonaire","38004"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520891","Department for International Development","false","2016-05-31","<p>I refer the Hon. Member to the answer I provided on 24 May to Question number 37332.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-05-31T10:17:23.973Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520891/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520891/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520891/answer",,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-05-23","Developing Countries: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, whether the Government plans to become a founding donor of the Education Cannot Wait fund for education in emergencies when it is launched at the World Humanitarian Summit 2016.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","38034"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520892","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-05-26","<p>The Ministry of Justice does not set a budget for food served in its offices. Catering services are provided by private companies under contract to the Ministry of Justice and provided to staff without subsidy. Spending on food is determined by the contractor based on sales receipts from Ministry of Justice staff.</p><p> </p><p>The Ministry of Justice has worked with its current suppliers to align existing contracts with the requirements of the balanced scorecard.</p><p> </p><p>Details of the proportion of food produced for the Ministry of Justice that was sourced from British producers is not recorded centrally and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>I refer the honourable member to the answer given to PQ 35065 on 29 April 2016 which provides relevant details about food procured for prisons.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-05-26T12:56:21.713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520892/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520892/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520892/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-05-23","Ministry of Justice: Food","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the annual budget is for food produced for his Department's offices; and what proportion of food produced for his Department was sourced from British producers in the last period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Nick Smith","Blaenau Gwent","Nick Smith","37831"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520893","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-05-26","<p>Prior to June 2015, information held centrally on prisoners serving sentences for drug related offences was not sufficiently detailed to identify offences relating to cannabis as opposed to other drugs. Providing data back to 2010 could therefore only be done at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>According to centrally held data, as at 30 June 2015 (latest available), there were 1,363 offenders in prison custody for cannabis related offences in England and Wales. This number includes all offenders who have had their offence categorised as a ‘drug offence’ and in which cannabis is explicitly stated in their offence description. This number does not include instances where cannabis may have been a contributing factor to the main offence committed.</p><p> </p><p>These figures have been drawn from administrative IT systems which, as with any large scale recording system, are subject to possible errors with data entry and processing.</p><p> </p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-05-26T10:01:10.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520893/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520893/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520893/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-05-23","Prison Sentences: Cannabis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many people were serving prison sentences for offences related to cannabis in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Jeff Smith","Manchester, Withington","Jeff Smith","37878"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520894","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-05-26","<p>The Ministry of Justice publishes quarterly figures on the number of children involved in Public or Private law orders made in Family courts in England and Wales. Data for 2011 to 2015 can be found in Table 4 via the link below: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/518299/tables-for-family-court-statistics-quarterly-q4-2015.xls" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/518299/tables-for-family-court-statistics-quarterly-q4-2015.xls</a></p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2016-05-26T10:33:34.05Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520894/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520894/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520894/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-05-23","Court Orders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many court orders have been issued following non-compliance with a child arrangement order in the latest period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Mr David Burrowes","Enfield, Southgate","Mr David Burrowes","38056"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520895","Leader of the House","false","2016-05-31","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer given to him by my right hon. Friend the Minister for the Cabinet Office on 31 May 2016, to Question UIN 37901.</p>","Epsom and Ewell","Chris Grayling",,"2016-05-31T15:37:31.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520895/answer","Biography information for Chris Grayling","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520895/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520895/answer",,,,,,,,"34","Leader of the House","Leader of the House","2016-05-23","Leader of the House of Commons: Food","1","House of Commons","To ask the Leader of the House, what the annual budget is for food produced for his Office; and what proportion of food produced for his Office was sourced from British producers in the last period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Nick Smith","Blaenau Gwent","Nick Smith","37832"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520896","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-05-26","<p>There is no specific budget allocated for food produced within the Departmen; figures which detail the origin of food produced are not held by my department.</p><p> </p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers",,"2016-05-26T10:43:54.78Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520896/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520896/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520896/answer",,,,,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-05-23","Northern Ireland Office: Food","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what the annual budget is for food produced for her Department's offices; and what proportion of food produced for her Department was sourced from British producers in the last period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Nick Smith","Blaenau Gwent","Nick Smith","37833"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520897","Scotland Office","false","2016-05-26","<p>The Scotland Office has no in-house catering facilities and the provision of food is generally limited to catering associated with official hospitality and is supplied by external contractors.</p><p> </p><p>The Office does not separately record the proportion of food sourced from British Producers used by its external caterers.</p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2016-05-26T09:41:37.34Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520897/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520897/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520897/answer",,,,,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2016-05-23","Scotland Office: Food","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what the annual budget is for food produced for his Department's offices; and what proportion of food produced for his Department was sourced from British producers in the last period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Nick Smith","Blaenau Gwent","Nick Smith","37834"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520898","Scotland Office","false","2016-05-26","<p>A variety of events are held in Dover House, both by Scotland Office Ministers and by third parties, throughout the year.</p><p>The events are aimed at engaging stakeholders on a wide variety of policy issues and aspects of life in Scotland.</p><p><br></p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell","38047 ; 38048 ; 38049 ; 38050","2016-05-26T09:44:58.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520898/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520898/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520898/answer",,,,,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2016-05-23","Dover House","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, how many public engagement events to support the voluntary sector in Scotland have been held at Dover House in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Douglas Chapman","Dunfermline and West Fife","Douglas Chapman","38051"
