"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520950","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-05-26","<p>Statistical information on people currently receiving Attendance Allowance (AA), including the numbers with a main disabling condition of inflammatory bowel disease, and their location, is available from the DWP Tabulation Tool: <a href="http://tabulation-tool.dwp.gov.uk/100pc/tabtool.html" target="_blank">http://tabulation-tool.dwp.gov.uk/100pc/tabtool.html</a>.</p><p> </p><p>These data relate to the claimant’s main disabling condition at the time their claim is awarded. Claimants may often have multiple disabling conditions, but these cannot be identified from the data the department holds. Therefore there may be other claimants in receipt of AA who have been diagnosed with inflammatory bowel disease who are not captured in the above data.</p><p> </p><p>Information on disabling conditions is not collected at the initial claim application stage.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","37993","2016-05-26T13:39:45.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520950/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520950/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520950/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-05-23","Attendance Allowance: Inflammatory Bowel Disease","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people applied for attendance allowance and were diagnosed with inflammatory bowel disease in (a) England and (b) Wales in the last five years.","false","Biography information for Andrew Percy","Brigg and Goole","Andrew Percy","37987"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520951","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-05-27","<p>Since launch, there have been over 2.4 million visits to the Pension Wise website and over 61,000 appointments, with the latest data showing a record number of appointments in March. To drive awareness of the service, Pension Wise has run three national marketing campaigns across TV, radio, print and digital media, the latest of which finished in April 2016.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, pension providers are required to signpost to Pension Wise when issuing retirement wake-up packs and Pension Wise guiders engage with local businesses and services to further raise awareness of the service.</p><p> </p><p>The Government recognises that people should have the freedom to access information in a way that is suitable to them.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-05-27T10:37:42.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520951/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520951/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520951/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-05-23","Pensions: Advisory Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps he is taking to improve take-up of the Pension Wise guidance service.","false","Biography information for Rachel Reeves","Leeds West","Rachel Reeves","38024"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520952","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-05-26","<p>The current Pension Wise service will continue to deliver guidance to people aged 50 years and over, with defined contribution pension pots, to help them understand their options under the pension freedoms.</p><p>The new pensions guidance body will take forward the services currently provided by three organisations: Pension Wise, The Pensions Advisory Service (TPAS) and the pension services offered by Money Advise Service (MAS). Until then these organisations will continue to support people in understanding and accessing their pensions.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-05-26T12:51:15.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520952/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520952/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520952/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-05-23","Pensions: Advisory Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps the Government plans to take to help people who will access their pensions before the proposed new pension guidance service becomes available in April 2018.","false","Biography information for Rachel Reeves","Leeds West","Rachel Reeves","38061"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521310","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-05-26","<p>The government was elected with a mandate to reform the UK’s human rights framework. The Crown Dependencies are not part of the UK but are self-governing dependencies of the Crown. This means they have their own directly elected legislative assemblies, administrative, fiscal and legal systems and their own courts of law. Although the Bill of Rights will not apply to the Crown Dependencies we have undertaken to fully engage with them.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2016-05-26T15:41:45.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521310/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521310/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521310/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-05-23","Bill of Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what discussions he has had with the Crown dependencies on the Government's plans to introduce a British Bill of Rights.","false","Biography information for Dr Lisa Cameron","East Kilbride, Strathaven and Lesmahagow","Dr Lisa Cameron","905095"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521753","Attorney General","false","2016-05-26","<p>Under existing law, a company only faces criminal liability if prosecutors can prove a sufficiently senior person knew about the criminal conduct. It can be extremely hard to prove this, especially in large companies with complex management structures.</p><p>A new failure to prevent offence could help prosecutors hold all companies to account for criminal conduct and bring some positive changes in corporate culture.</p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2016-05-26T12:18:22.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521753/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521753/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521753/answer",,,,,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2016-05-23","Fraud: Crime Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of introducing a new criminal offence of failure to prevent economic crime on the number of prosecutions for such crimes.","false","Biography information for Glyn Davies","Montgomeryshire","Glyn Davies","905130"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521754","Attorney General","false","2016-05-26","<p>The Government's position is that the UK will be stronger, safer and better off remaining in a reformed EU.</p><p>Through participation in the European Arrest Warrant, the UK is able to extradite foreign suspects and bring suspects back to the UK more quickly and economically. Since April 2011, it has enabled us to transfer around 5,500 suspects out of the UK and to bring back around 650 to face justice here.</p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2016-05-26T12:14:48.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521754/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521754/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521754/answer",,,,,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2016-05-23","Prosecutions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the UK leaving the EU on the Government's ability to prosecute criminals who have left the UK.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","905128"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521755","Women and Equalities","false","2016-05-31","<p>The detention of pregnant women under Immigration Act powers occurs only in very limited situations, either where there is a clear prospect of early removal or in very exceptional circumstances. Very few pregnant women are detained. Central recording of the number of detained women who have disclosed their pregnancy started in August 2015. Options for the collection of wider data on pregnant women is being considered as part of the Immigration Act 2016 implementation.</p><p> </p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2016-05-31T11:44:33.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521755/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521755/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521755/answer",,,,,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2016-05-23","Immigrants: Detainees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, what discussions she has had with the Secretary of State for Home Affairs on the number of pregnant women who have been detained for immigration purposes since central recording statistics on such cases began and the outcomes of their detention.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","905126"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519873","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-05-31","<p>Since 6<sup>th</sup> April this year, UK companies (with exception of listed companies), limited liability partnerships and societates europaeae have been required to hold a register of people with significant control (PSC register). The register records the ultimate owners and controllers of UK companies. It is designed to record individuals. However, where a company is owned by another company that is also required to hold a PSC register, or is subject to equivalent disclosure requirements, those companies should be recorded on the register.</p><p> </p><p>Where a company is owned and or controlled by a third party incorporation agent including Trust and Company Service Providers (TCSP) and they are also required to hold a PSC register or are subject to equivalent transparency requirements then they would be required to be registered on that company’s PSC register. If the third party incorporation agent is not required to hold its own PSC register then the UK company would be required to look further up the ownership chain to identify who owns and controls the TCSP. The ultimate owner would be recorded on the PSC register.</p><p> </p><p>Where a third party incorporation agent has incorporated a company on behalf of someone else and they do not own or control the company, then the register would not record the third party incorporation agent details. It would instead record who actually owns and controls that UK company.</p><p> </p><p>How the PSC register works is explained in detailed guidance that has been prepared by BIS with the help of a working group of businesses, lawyers and civil society organisations. The guidance can be found here: <a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/publications/guidance-to-the-people-with-significant-control-requirements-for-companies-and-limited-liability-partnerships" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/publications/guidance-to-the-people-with-significant-control-requirements-for-companies-and-limited-liability-partnerships</a>.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-05-31T13:10:19.04Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519873/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519873/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519873/answer","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519873/answer/previousversion/665",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519873/answer/previousversion/665","Biography information for Anna Soubry","26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-05-20","Companies: Ownership","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, whether it is his policy that the proposed public register of beneficial owners of companies will provide details of the names of (a) trust or company service providers and (b) other third parties which incorporate those companies.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","37717"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519874","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-06-07","<p>The Government considers that the date of birth of company directors is an important identifier for those searching the public companies register as it allows searchers to distinguish between individuals with the same, or similar, names.</p><p> </p><p>Following feedback from company directors about the availability of their full date of birth on the public register, section 96 of the Small Business, Enterprise and Employment Act 2015 requires the Registrar of Companies to suppress the “day” element of a director’s date of birth.</p><p> </p><p>This strikes an appropriate balance between ensuring that the information on the public register is of real practical use and reducing the risk that the information becomes a tool for abuse by exposing individuals to the risk of identity theft or fraud.</p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-06-07T10:38:47.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519874/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519874/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519874/answer","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519874/answer/previousversion/664",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519874/answer/previousversion/664","Biography information for Anna Soubry","26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-05-20","Directors: Disclosure of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, for what reason Companies House publishes the month and year of birth of company directors.","false","Biography information for Dr Tania Mathias","Twickenham","Dr Tania Mathias","37754"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519875","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-05-25","<p>The table below shows the number of referrals (complaints) from the Pay and Work Rights Helpline (PWRH) to relevant enforcement authorities for the 2010/11 to 2013/14 financial years.</p><p> </p><p><strong>Table 1: Referrals from the PWRH to each enforcement agencies, 2010/11 to 2013/14</strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>2010/11</p></td><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>2013/14</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>HMRC</p></td><td><p>2,080</p></td><td><p>2,440</p></td><td><p>2,610</p></td><td><p>3,690</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>EAS</p></td><td><p>490</p></td><td><p>530</p></td><td><p>600</p></td><td><p>630</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>HSE</p></td><td><p>200</p></td><td><p>250</p></td><td><p>210</p></td><td><p>250</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>DEFRA</p></td><td><p>280</p></td><td><p>210</p></td><td><p>200</p></td><td><p>150</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>GLA</p></td><td><p>60</p></td><td><p>70</p></td><td><p>50</p></td><td><p>50</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>*The Pay and Work Rights Helpline opened in May 2009</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong>Notes</strong></p><p>1. Numbers are rounded to the nearest 10.</p><p>2. Calls can be referred to more than one agency so the sum does not amount to the total number of calls referred for the period.</p><p>3. Calls referred to agencies include complaints, complex queries and calls where intelligence was passed to other agencies.</p><p>4. Figures include referrals via all PWRH communication channels, including telephone calls, post and online complaints.</p><p>5. These figures are based on final data submitted by BSS on closure at the end of March 2015. They may not reconcile with provisional data provided while the old helpline was operational.</p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-05-25T15:28:13.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519875/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519875/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519875/answer",,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-05-20","Employment: Telephone Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, with reference to the Answer of 31 March 2016 to Question 31997, on employment: telephone services, if he will provide that data for financial years (a) 2010-11, (b) 2011-12, (c) 2012-13 and (d) 2013-14.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","37757"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519876","Cabinet Office","false","2016-06-01","<p>A list of attendees at the Anti-Corruption Summit has now been published on gov.uk and laid in the library of the House.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-06-01T15:51:14.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519876/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519876/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519876/answer",,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-05-20","Anti-corruption Summit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will publish a list of the people who attended the Anti-Corruption Summit on 12 May 2016.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","37712"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519877","Cabinet Office","false","2016-05-25","<p>The Tackling Corruption Together conference on 11 May was organised by a consortium of civil society organisations, businesses and the Commonwealth Secretariat. The government was not responsible for the guest list.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-05-25T16:58:27.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519877/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519877/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519877/answer",,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-05-20","Tackling Corruption Together Conference","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will publish a list of the people who attended the Tackling Corruption Together Conference on 11 May 2016.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","37714"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519878","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-06-06","The procedure governing a country’s departure from the EU is set out in Article 50 of the Treaty on European Union. This provides for a period of two years for the negotiation of exit terms. EU laws would continue to apply to the departing Member State until the Article 50 agreement had entered into force, or for two years if no agreement had been reached and no extension to the two year period had been granted. A request for an extension could only be granted with the unanimous agreement of the remaining Member States.","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2016-06-06T15:36:05.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519878/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519878/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519878/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-20","UK Membership of EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of whether UK citizens would retain ownership rights over property elsewhere in the EU during the period prior to the completion of Article 50 negotiations relating to the Lisbon Treaty in the event of the UK voting to leave the EU.","false","Biography information for Mr Ben Bradshaw","Exeter","Mr Ben Bradshaw","37722"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519879","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-06-06","The procedure governing a country’s departure from the EU is set out in Article 50 of the Treaty on European Union. This provides for a period of two years for the negotiation of exit terms. EU laws would continue to apply to the departing Member State until the Article 50 agreement had entered into force, or for two years if no agreement had been reached and no extension to the two year period had been granted. A request for an extension could only be granted with the unanimous agreement of the remaining Member States.","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2016-06-06T15:45:46.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519879/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519879/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519879/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-05-20","UK Membership of EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether UK citizens will have the rights that currently apply to access public services in the EU in the event of the UK leaving the EU and prior to the completion of exit negotiations under Article 50 of the Lisbon Treaty.","false","Biography information for Mr Ben Bradshaw","Exeter","Mr Ben Bradshaw","37723"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519880","Cabinet Office","false","2016-05-25","<p>We remain committed to this reform and will publish draft legislation in due course.</p>","Weston-super-Mare","John Penrose",,"2016-05-25T17:37:40.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519880/answer","Biography information for John Penrose","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519880/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519880/answer",,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-05-20","Public Sector: Ombudsman","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, when he plans to publish a draft Public Service Ombudsman Bill.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","37716"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519881","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-05-31","<p>At the International Anti-Corruption Summit in London on 12 May, my Rt hon Friend the Prime Minister announced that we will require foreign companies that own or purchase UK properties or bid on UK Government procurement contracts to provide details of their beneficial owners to a public central register. This will be the first register of its kind in the world.</p><p> </p><p>The Department for Business, Innovation and Skills will consult with experts to develop the policy throughout the year and consult formally on the detail of the policy in due course. Implementation of the new register requirements is expected to require both primary and secondary legislation, which we intend to introduce when Parliamentary time allows.</p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","37733","2016-05-31T14:04:30.23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519881/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519881/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519881/answer",,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-05-20","Foreign Companies: Property","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, with reference to the press release, PM holds major summit as part of global drive to expose, punish and drive out corruption, published on 12 May 2016, what the timetable is for the (a) formulation and (b) implementation of the Government's plans to require foreign companies that own property in the UK to declare their real owners.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","37730"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519882","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-05-31","<p>At the International Anti-Corruption Summit in London on 12 May, my Rt hon Friend the Prime Minister announced that we will require foreign companies that own or purchase UK properties or bid on UK Government procurement contracts to provide details of their beneficial owners to a public central register. This will be the first register of its kind in the world.</p><p> </p><p>The Department for Business, Innovation and Skills will consult with experts to develop the policy throughout the year and consult formally on the detail of the policy in due course. Implementation of the new register requirements is expected to require both primary and secondary legislation, which we intend to introduce when Parliamentary time allows.</p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","37730","2016-05-31T14:04:30.293Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519882/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519882/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519882/answer",,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-05-20","Foreign Companies: Property","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, with reference to the press release, PM holds major summit as part of global drive to expose, punish and drive out corruption, published on 12 May 2016, whether he plans to bring forward legislative proposals requiring foreign companies that own property in the UK to declare their real owners.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","37733"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519883","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-06-03","<p>At the International Anti-Corruption Summit in London on 12 May, my Rt hon Friend the Prime Minister announced that we will require foreign companies that own or purchase UK properties or bid on UK government procurement contracts to provide details of their beneficial owners to a public central register. This will be the first register of its kind in the world.</p><p> </p><p>The Department for Business, Innovation and Skills will consult on the detail of the policy later this year. The Prime Minister has committed to a publicly accessible register of foreign company beneficial ownership on which we plan to consult in due course.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-06-03T09:56:16.333Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519883/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519883/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519883/answer","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519883/answer/previousversion/662",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519883/answer/previousversion/662","Biography information for Anna Soubry","26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-05-20","Foreign Companies: Property","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, with reference to the press release, PM hosts major summit as part of global drive to expose, publish and drive out corruption, published on 12 May 2016, whether he plans to publish information on the ownership of property in the UK owned by foreign companies.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","37744"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519884","Cabinet Office","false","2016-06-09","<p>44 countries (including the UK) attended the Anti-Corruption Summit on 12 May. A attach a list.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-06-09T12:47:03.853Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519884/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519884/answer","Final Attendance List for publication ACS 12 May 2016 .xlsx","Final Attendance List for publication ACS 12 May 2016 .xlsx","Excel List of Countries for Member ","Excel List of Countries for Member ","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519884/answer",,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-05-20","Anti-corruption Summit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, which countries attended the Anti-Corruption Summit on 12 May 2016.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","37749"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519885","HM Treasury","false","2016-05-26","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) works closely with the Child Maintenance Service as well as other Government Departments to ensure that all allegations of tax evasion from members of the public are assessed, dealt with appropriately and a decision made on the most appropriate course of action.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC values the information they receive from the public and business community. Clamping down on those who try to cheat the system through evading taxes and over claiming benefits is a key priority for the Government and we are committed to ensuring the tax system operates fairly and efficiently.</p><p> </p><p>Any information received is passed on to HMRC’s Enforcement and Compliance teams. This can result in recovery of funds, education to help support compliance civil or criminal action depending on the severity of the evasion.</p><p> </p><p>More serious cases can result in prosecution action by HMRC’s Fraud Investigation Service</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","37748","2016-05-26T13:21:48.13Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519885/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519885/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519885/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-20","Children: Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what procedures are in place to ensure that when a receiving parent has been advised by the Child Maintenance Service to contact HM Revenue and Customs to report possible tax evasion by a paying parent that possible evasion is investigated to ensure levels of child maintenance reflects full income.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","37747"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519886","HM Treasury","false","2016-05-26","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) works closely with the Child Maintenance Service as well as other Government Departments to ensure that all allegations of tax evasion from members of the public are assessed, dealt with appropriately and a decision made on the most appropriate course of action.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC values the information they receive from the public and business community. Clamping down on those who try to cheat the system through evading taxes and over claiming benefits is a key priority for the Government and we are committed to ensuring the tax system operates fairly and efficiently.</p><p> </p><p>Any information received is passed on to HMRC’s Enforcement and Compliance teams. This can result in recovery of funds, education to help support compliance civil or criminal action depending on the severity of the evasion.</p><p> </p><p>More serious cases can result in prosecution action by HMRC’s Fraud Investigation Service</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","37747","2016-05-26T13:21:48.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519886/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519886/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519886/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-20","Children: Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will establish an investigation unit within HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) to deal with cases in which the receiving parent has been advised by the Child Maintenance Service to contact HMRC to report possible tax evasion by the paying parent.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","37748"
