"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519890","Department for Education","false","2016-05-26","<p>60 of the 130 academies and free schools that have been re-brokered since 2010 had been graded inadequate by Ofsted.</p><p> </p><p>The remaining academies and free schools were re-brokered because Regional Schools Commissioners identified weaknesses in those schools that could be better addressed by a new sponsor.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2016-05-26T16:34:11.713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519890/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519890/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519890/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-05-20","Academies: Sponsorship","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to the Answer of 11 May 2016 to Question 35798, on Academies Sponsorship, how many of the re-brokered schools in each year since 2010 had been graded inadequate by Ofsted.","false","Biography information for Jess Phillips","Birmingham, Yardley","Jess Phillips","37729"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519891","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-05-26","<p>The procedure governing a country’s departure from the EU is set out in Article 50 of the Treaty on European Union. This provides for a period of two years for the negotiation of exit terms. The EU Treaties would continue to apply to the departing Member State until the Article 50 agreement had entered into force, or for two years if no agreement had been reached and no extension to the two year period had been granted. A request for an extension could only be granted with the unanimous agreement of the remaining Member States. The Government's position is that the UK will be stronger, safer and better off remaining in a reformed EU.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-05-26T10:28:17.95Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519891/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519891/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519891/answer",,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-05-20","Higher Education: Admissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, whether UK citizens will have the rights that currently apply to access higher education in the EU in the event of the UK leaving the EU and prior to the completion of exit negotiations under Article 50 of the Lisbon Treaty.","false","Biography information for Mr Ben Bradshaw","Exeter","Mr Ben Bradshaw","37720"
